<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,1660,2838,2863]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 62-68 mm, tail 45-60 mm, ear 8-9 mm, hindfoot 15-17 mm; weight 7-12 g. The Eastern Harvest Mouse is among the smallest species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1439,1652,2908,2941]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Reithrodontomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Reithrodontomys</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is brownish to dark brown, sometimes faintly washed with gray, and has dark mid-dorsal stripe. Sides are paler than dorsum and usually have lateral line stripe. Venter is ash-colored, with cinnamon or pinkish infusion. Tail is slender and sparsely haired. Ears are fuscous or fuscous black, and feet are grayish white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1400,1511,3105,3138]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Habitat.</emphasis>
Wooded or grassland habitats with dense understory, old fields, abandoned fields, and croplands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1400,2602,3187,3216]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" box="[1400,2602,3187,3216]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1400,1654,3187,3216]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Eastern Harvest Mouse eats seeds, green vegetation, and insects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1400,1534,3223,3256]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Breeding.</emphasis>
The Eastern Harvest Mouse has reproductive peaks in spring and autumn. Gestation is c.21 days, and litters have 1-8 young.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1398,2388,3305,3334]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" box="[1398,2388,3305,3334]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1398,1633,3305,3334]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Eastern Harvest Mouse is presumably nocturnal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1399,2116,3345,3374]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Mean home ranges are 905-1 m? for males and 1094-5 m* for females. Eastern Harvest Mice are not thought to be territorial.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1399,2449,3459,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="93.[1398,2605,2759,3492]" box="[1399,2449,3459,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1399,1748,3459,3492]" pageId="93" pageNumber="371">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
